Kiess's Wall Command treats Priest practitioners as critical logistics: sustained healing capacity determines how long a defensive position can be held under pressure, and the Wall Command's preparedness doctrine classifies Priest deployment as an operational multiplier. Wall Command assessors evaluate Priests by sustained channel duration (how long they can maintain continuous output) and compound condition capacity (how many simultaneous status conditions they can address in a single channel). The frontier context means Priests in Kiess accumulate genuine experience with delayed progression conditions and spiritually contaminated wounds — both are common in frontier engagement situations — rather than primarily treating urban acute trauma. The ward-network infrastructure at Wall posts is a specific Wall Command responsibility; Priests who maintain wall-adjacent ward-networks receive integrated support from the Wall Command logistics system. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant framework benefits Priest practitioners who would otherwise be compelled to serve specific private parties rather than collective security functions.

