Rakuen's relationship with the Priest tradition is organized around the communal survival framework: ward-networks are collective infrastructure, healing capacity is a community resource, and Priest practitioners who maintain either are performing recognized community-function roles. The Ember Wardens' formal integration of healing capacity into emergency response doctrine means Priest practitioners in Rakuen have a clearer operational role than in cities where they work primarily in institutional shrine contexts. The chronic emergency posture creates demand for sustained miracle-channel expertise that exceeds what most cities' Priest communities develop: Rakuen Priests see extended simultaneous multi-patient situations regularly enough that compound condition methodology is standard practice rather than specialty capability. The communal burden-sharing ethos creates pressure on Priests to operate at the sustainable capacity end of the tradition's internal debate — the community cannot afford to lose its healing infrastructure periodically because practitioners have overextended themselves. The Ember Wardens function as informal enforcer of sustainable capacity doctrine: they will pull Priests from active channel operations when visible overextension threatens practitioner collapse.

