Khenari death doctrine positions healing as an intervention in the natural departure process — extending life delays descent, which is theologically acceptable when the descent is not yet completed but becomes problematic when healing is applied to maintain life beyond what the death-ledger would indicate is the natural closure point. In Midgaard, Khenari Priests navigate this by treating healing as completion support: their practice is framed as sustaining the patient long enough for all nine descent stages to be properly prepared for when the time comes, rather than indefinitely deferring departure. The more significant tension is around ward-network maintenance: Khenari ward-networks in Midgaard's mortuary districts include wards against specific types of spiritual entities that Khenari theology classifies as incomplete descents, and the maintenance protocols for those wards require Khenari death-ledger coordination to ensure the wards are targeting the right classification of entity. Khenari Priests in Midgaard are disproportionately represented in ward-network maintenance roles because their death-ledger precision translates directly to accurate ward-anchor classification, reducing the risk of ward systems that inadvertently exclude entities that should be protected against.

